8":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Scotland":"Skotland","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"Street, Kent, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1260–1342":"1260–1342","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","1275":"1275","1260":"1260","about 1275":"circa 1275","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Scotland":"Schotland","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"Street, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1260–1342":"1260–1342","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","1275":"1275","1260":"1260","about 1275":"about 1275","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Scotland":"Scotland","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"Street, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"LATIMER","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a Latinist, a clerk who wrote documents in Latin, from Anglo-Norman French <i>latinier</i>, <i>latim(m)ier</i>. Latin was more or less the universal language of official documents in the Middle Ages, displaced only gradually by the vernacular – in England, by Anglo-Norman French at first, and eventually by English."],"variants":[{"name":"Latner","meanings":["English: occupational name for a worker in or maker of latten or brass, from Middle English <i>latoun</i> ‘brass’ (Old French <i>laton</i>). This name may sometimes have been confused with   Latimer  .","Altered form of German   Lattner   or   Lettner  ."]},{"name":"Lattimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Latimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattimer","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattner","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  .","German: occupational name for a carpenter who prepared or used laths or slats, from Middle High German <i>latte</i> ‘slat, lath’ + <i>-n</i> (plural suffix) + the agent suffix <i>-er</i>."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":55,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":68,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":77,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Joan de LATIMER was born in 1260, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Alasdair Comyn. She died in 1342, at the age of 82."},"et":{"1260–1342":"1260–1342","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315